\section{Legacy encodings}
\subsection{Pseudo-Unicode encodings}
A ``pseudo-Unicode'' encoding is currently in use on Wikipedia and elsewhere. This ``encoding'', to the extent that it is one, mixes SVG glyphs, HTML markup, and a few Unicode characters intended for other purposes.

\begin{listarea}
\listitem{U+1BA01--1BA0F are represented with SVG's;}
\listitem{U+0323, the \font[features=+smcp]{Combining Dot Below}, is used as in this document; and}
\listitem{U+0305, the \font[features=+smcp]{Combining Overline}, is represented variably by a CSS \code{\hbox{border-top}}, or else by a \font[features=+smcp]{Combining Macron} (U+0304) or other script-inappropriate combining mark. It seems this is done due to lack of font support for combining marks over katakana.}
\end{listarea}

A second pseudo-Unicode encoding exists, which I call the ``\Href[src=https://twitter.com/taipalogy/status/1282245269820551169]{Taipa encoding}''. It misuses characters like U+27E8, \font[features=+smcp]{Mathematical Left Angle Bracket}, because of its similar appearance to tone 5, \tkana{𛨄}. It does not seem to have widely caught on outside of Taipa's tweets; certainly this kind of misuse is a good reason to introduce real characters for the task.

\subsection{Mojiky\={o}}

Mojiky\={o} almost fully supports Taiwanese kana. Its only deficiency is that it is missing \tkana{オ̅} and \tkana{ゥ̅}, which means that the Quanzhou dialect is not reproducible in the Mojiky\={o} encoding.

In Mojiky\={o}, the Taiwanese kana are available in the font \code{\hbox{Mojikm0D.TTF}}; 20 codepoints are devoted to them. Mojiky\={o} chooses to encode the \font[features=+smcp]{Combining Overline} as precombined with the kana it combines with, and it encodes the \font[features=+smcp]{Combining Dot Below} as a spacing mark.

